Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War.
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of Chinese Lunar New Year and Beijing Winter Olympics celebrations.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any agreement and certainly required painstaking preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given a free hand to Putin to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and consider his later confirmation as head for life of China this year a mere formality.
After concentrating all power in his hands, Xi has carefully prepared the scenario in which he will be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After securing Xi's support, Putin set out to fulfill his lifelong dream with incredible brutality.
As he approaches his 70th year, Putin believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, it's now or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar they can blindly follow.
It's precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it's a vision that distorts 'the Russian soul', emotional to the point of sentimentalism.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers on several occasions when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I found out that they are willing to share their last piece of bread with you if you ask them.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, disintegration had already begun.
I've created a foundation in Russia, and then done the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I founded a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't know Putin personally, but I've observed his rise from very close, being aware of his cruelty.
He has reduced the Chechen capital, Grozny, to nothing, and he threatens to do the same with the Ukrainian capital, Kyiv.
Poutine was once a cunning KGB operator, but it seems he has changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be quite on the same side as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have put in place an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that seems to be unstoppable.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are truly one people, and that Ukrainians were misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 2014 Euromaidan protests.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a black rage.
But the Russian army made a poor showing when it was ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
Deep-seated corruption in the awarding of defense contracts also played an important role in its insufficient results.
However, rather than blaming himself, Poutine has literally gone crazy.
He has decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to be acting without encountering the slightest resistance.
He unleashes the entire Russian army into battle and disregards all the rules of war, particularly by indiscriminately bombing the civilian population.
Many hospitals have been hit and the power grid that feeds the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In the besieged city of Mariupol, 400,000 people were left without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia might well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive arms to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to buy Russian-made MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already achieved miracles by strengthening the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, Xi appears to have realized that Putin is acting alone.
On March 8, a day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that friendship between China and Russia remain "solid", Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to say he supported their efforts to restore peace.
He wanted to express the utmost restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will accede to Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi are removed before they destroy our civilization.
